i-eun Kim recounts the story of the almost 1,200 Japanese medical students who rushed to German universities to learn cutting-edge knowledge from the world leaders in medicine, and of the dozen German physicians who were invited to Japan to transform the country’s medical institutions and education.Shifting fluently between German, English, and Japanese sources, Kim’s book uses the colourful lives of these men to examine the impact of German medicine in Japan from its arrival to the pinnacle of its influence and its abrupt but temporary collapse at the outbreak of the First World War.Transnational history at its finest, Doctors of Empire not only illuminates the German origins of modern medical science in Japan but also reinterprets the nature of German imperialism in East Asia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aMedical educationxHistoryx19th centuryxGermany. 0aMedical educationxHistoryx19th centuryxJapan. 0aMedical educationzGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 0aMedical educationzJapanxHistoryy19th century. 0aMedicinexHistoryx19th centuryxGermany. 0aMedicinexHistoryx19th centuryxJapan. 0aMedicinexInternational cooperationxHistoryx19th centuryxGermany. 0aMedicinexInternational cooperationxHistoryx19th centuryxJapan. 0aMedicinezGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 0aMedicinezGermanyxInternational cooperationxHistoryy19th century. 0aMedicinezJapanxHistoryy19th century. 0aMedicinezJapanxInternational cooperationxHistoryy19th century. 0aPhysiciansxHistoryx19th centuryxGermany. 0aPhysiciansxHistoryx19th centuryxJapan. 0aPhysicianszGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 0aPhysicianszJapanxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060